717
00:39:17.202 --> 00:39:19.670
Shut the door please, Miss O'Shea.

718
00:39:23.174 --> 00:39:24.198
You're late.

719
00:39:24.275 --> 00:39:26.470
I won't waste time with introductions.
These are our collaborators.


720
00:39:26.544 --> 00:39:28.068
- Hi, kids.
- Hi.


721
00:39:28.146 --> 00:39:30.671
As I was saying, I've worked out
a series of cross-references


722
00:39:30.749 --> 00:39:32.842
which I believe will be the best approach
to our subject.


723
00:39:32.917 --> 00:39:34.350
Going like gangbusters, isn't he?

724
00:39:34.419 --> 00:39:36.080
Sit down, please.

725
00:39:39.424 --> 00:39:42.621
I don't think
you'll find our venture dull, Miss O'Shea.


726
00:39:42.694 --> 00:39:46.528
The scientific conquest of
an important subject is never dull.


727
00:39:47.298 --> 00:39:49.960
"Slang," as the poet
Carl Sandburg has said,


728
00:39:50.035 --> 00:39:51.696
"is language which takes off its coat,

729
00:39:51.770 --> 00:39:53.931
"spits on its hands and goes to work."

730
00:39:54.005 --> 00:39:56.906
Let us... Let us, too,
then get down to work.


731
00:40:03.581 --> 00:40:06.482
Well, we've accomplished a lot
in the last three days,


732
00:40:06.551 --> 00:40:09.076
and I'm very grateful to all of you.

733
00:40:09.154 --> 00:40:11.645
There's another word
I'd like to take up now.


734
00:40:11.723 --> 00:40:13.782
It's recurred several times
in our discussions,


735
00:40:13.858 --> 00:40:15.849
and its meaning still eludes me.

736
00:40:15.927 --> 00:40:17.519
I think it was Miss O'Shea
who used it yesterday


737
00:40:17.595 --> 00:40:20.223
in reference to the cuffs that I wear.

738
00:40:20.298 --> 00:40:23.028
- The word is "corny."
- Yeah, wouldn't you say they were corny?


739
00:40:23.101 --> 00:40:26.468
- Because of the cornstarch in them?
- Because it's 1941.


740
00:40:27.205 --> 00:40:31.164
- Then corny means old-fashioned.
- Kind of hick, loose-tooth.


741
00:40:31.242 --> 00:40:32.766
Mortimer Snerd.

742
00:40:33.578 --> 00:40:35.136
Oh, gee.

743
00:40:35.747 --> 00:40:37.408
There's other kinds of corn, too.

744
00:40:37.482 --> 00:40:39.143
When you give your girl
your fraternity pin,


745
00:40:39.217 --> 00:40:41.515
well, if she says, "I'll keep it forever,"

746
00:40:41.586 --> 00:40:43.850
- that's corny, too.
- Yeah, or take a joke.


747
00:40:43.922 --> 00:40:45.719
"That's no lady, that's my wife."

748
00:40:45.790 --> 00:40:48.122
Making your baby's shoes into ashtrays.

749
00:40:48.193 --> 00:40:49.558
- That's corn.
- Right off the cob.


750
00:40:49.627 --> 00:40:51.925
Well, let's stick to corn.

751
00:40:51.996 --> 00:40:53.861
Is it synonymous with baloney?

752
00:40:53.932 --> 00:40:57.026
No, it's anything
that gets them in the sticks.


753
00:40:57.102 --> 00:40:59.696
"Long time, no see," that's Indian corn.

754
00:40:59.771 --> 00:41:01.329
Yeah, when a guy comes to see a girl
and says,


755
00:41:01.406 --> 00:41:03.237
"Let's turn off the lights,
it hurts my eyes."


756
00:41:03.308 --> 00:41:05.003
Brother, that's corn.

757
00:41:05.076 --> 00:41:08.136
The implication is
he's trying to pull some hoytoytoy.


758
00:41:08.213 --> 00:41:12.172
- You're catching on, Professor.
- Countrified, old-fashioned, sentimental.


759
00:41:25.196 --> 00:41:26.686
Business kind of peaked, Jack?

760
00:41:26.765 --> 00:41:29.666
Yeah, it takes up a lot of time
being on the faculty.


761
00:41:29.734 --> 00:41:31.702
- I'll buy the heap.
- There's no call for you to do that.


762
00:41:31.770 --> 00:41:33.601
Why not?
I want to line my bureau drawers.


763
00:41:33.671 --> 00:41:34.797
Gee, thanks.

764
00:41:35.573 --> 00:41:38.804
- Back in a second, Professor.
- Oh, yes, all right.


765
00:41:52.791 --> 00:41:54.952
- Miss O'Shea.
- Just a minute.


766
00:41:59.230 --> 00:42:00.356
- Miss O'Shea.
- Yeah?


767
00:42:00.431 --> 00:42:02.296
We saw you pass the library arch,

768
00:42:02.367 --> 00:42:04.665
and we kind of got a little problem
on our hands.


769
00:42:04.736 --> 00:42:06.169
- Would you help us?
- Why, I'd love to.


770
00:42:06.237 --> 00:42:07.261
Oh, good.

771
00:42:08.072 --> 00:42:10.040
You're kind of spruced up today,
aren't you, Professor?


772
00:42:10.108 --> 00:42:11.735
- The spats?
- Yeah.


773
00:42:11.810 --> 00:42:15.439
I ran across them in my bottom drawer.
Why let the moths eat them?


774
00:42:15.513 --> 00:42:17.572
Attaboy. What's your problem, sweetie?

775
00:42:17.649 --> 00:42:19.514
- Well, look.
- Let me start again.


776
00:42:19.717 --> 00:42:21.742
But, Professor,
I'm completely exhausted.


777
00:42:21.820 --> 00:42:25.017
But we've got to get it right.
Now, start with the right foot.


778
00:42:25.089 --> 00:42:26.750
- The left foot.
- The right foot.


779
00:42:26.825 --> 00:42:27.883
Gentlemen, it's the left foot.

780
00:42:27.959 --> 00:42:30.018
- Which foot, please?
- The right foot.


781
00:42:30.094 --> 00:42:32.187
All right, but you're wrong.

782
00:42:32.697 --> 00:42:34.892
One, two, three, four.

783
00:42:34.966 --> 00:42:37.366
One, two, three.

784
00:42:37.435 --> 00:42:39.903
But I can't "humph" from here.

785
00:42:41.105 --> 00:42:44.268
We've been working on it
ever since luncheon.


786
00:42:44.342 --> 00:42:45.468
Holy smoke.

787
00:42:45.543 --> 00:42:49.138
- Start again with the left foot, come on.
- The left foot.


788
00:42:51.349 --> 00:42:53.783
One, two, three.

789
00:42:54.919 --> 00:42:56.614
Well, it's the right motion.

790
00:42:56.688 --> 00:43:00.055
- But it doesn't feel right.
- It doesn't look right.


791
00:43:00.592 --> 00:43:02.389
Possibly it isn't right.

792
00:43:02.460 --> 00:43:04.792
There was two "humphs." Humph, humph.

793
00:43:04.863 --> 00:43:07.297
Well, that would make it right.
Humph, humph.


794
00:43:08.132 --> 00:43:09.394
You're wrong, my dear Gurkakoff.

795
00:43:09.467 --> 00:43:12.095
Mathematics can never be wrong.
Look here, I'll show you.


796
00:43:12.170 --> 00:43:14.400
- Stay there, Professor Oddly.
- Show him.


797
00:43:16.140 --> 00:43:17.573
One, two.

798
00:43:17.642 --> 00:43:19.439
Professor Oddly, please stand up.

799
00:43:19.510 --> 00:43:20.738
I beg your pardon.

800
00:43:20.812 --> 00:43:24.373
- One, two, three. Humph, humph.
- Just one.


801
00:43:25.450 --> 00:43:28.214
- The expert is here. We need you.
- What's the trouble?


802
00:43:28.286 --> 00:43:30.117
Well, that dance you showed us last night.

803
00:43:30.188 --> 00:43:31.917
- Yeah?
- Yes, maybe we're not very bright.


804
00:43:31.990 --> 00:43:35.790
Professor Gurkakoff has been trying
to reconstruct it by compound fractions.


805
00:43:35.860 --> 00:43:38.192
- You'd better relax, lover.
- Who, me? Thank you.


806
00:43:38.263 --> 00:43:42.222
I can't find the common denominator
between the steps and the music.


807
00:43:42.300 --> 00:43:44.996
You bet you can't, you're playing
a polka, and I taught you a conga.


808
00:43:45.069 --> 00:43:47.697
How about some light in here? Come on.

809
00:43:48.506 --> 00:43:50.406
Look, kids, this is the tempo.

810
00:43:54.045 --> 00:43:55.273
Got it?

811
00:43:59.317 --> 00:44:01.649
- That's right, hit it.
- Hit what?


812
00:44:01.719 --> 00:44:03.346
That's what I told you.

813
00:44:03.755 --> 00:44:07.714
- One, two, three...
- Attaboy, Gurky! You're wonderful!


814
00:44:09.527 --> 00:44:12.223
Wing it, Professor. Hang on.

815
00:44:13.464 --> 00:44:14.931
Good afternoon.

816
00:44:17.201 --> 00:44:18.463
How do you like the new suit?

817
00:44:18.536 --> 00:44:20.663
What the well-dressed professor will wear.

818
00:44:20.738 --> 00:44:23.172
A young lady chased me all the way up
Fifth Avenue.


819
00:44:23.241 --> 00:44:25.209
Probably to tell you
to take the price tag off.


820
00:44:25.276 --> 00:44:27.244
Did you... Did you get the records?

821
00:44:27.312 --> 00:44:29.746
<i>Well, they were all out of
Beat Me Daddy, Eight to the Bar.</i>


822
00:44:29.814 --> 00:44:31.714
<i>- Oh, dear, oh, dear.
- But I got Chicka Chicka Boom Boom</i>


823
00:44:31.783 --> 00:44:35.480
<i>- and Shoot the Sherbet to Me Herbert.
- Now watch us go.</i>


824
00:44:37.989 --> 00:44:39.183
Thank you very much, gentlemen.

825
00:44:39.257 --> 00:44:41.316
The same time tomorrow,
all of you who can.


826
00:44:41.392 --> 00:44:43.360
- Okay, coach, so long.
- Goodbye.


827
00:44:43.428 --> 00:44:46.329
This has given me
a new interest in life, Doc.


828
00:44:46.397 --> 00:44:47.421
Me, too.

829
00:44:47.498 --> 00:44:49.864
I'm gonna use some of those
two-dollar words hollering my papers.


830
00:44:49.934 --> 00:44:53.893
Park Avenue bigamy scandal,
most illuminating, most illuminating!


831
00:44:53.972 --> 00:44:56.236
- So long, Prof.
- And thank you very much.


832
00:44:56.307 --> 00:44:57.604
That's all right.

833
00:44:57.675 --> 00:44:59.472
Excuse me for talking shop,

834
00:44:59.544 --> 00:45:02.411
but your garbage certainly
has cheered up these days.


835
00:45:02.480 --> 00:45:07.179
Flowers, candy boxes, perfume wrappings
and an empty of that sweet French liqueur.


836
00:45:07.251 --> 00:45:10.152
Why, that's not our garbage,
I'm sure.


837
00:45:10.221 --> 00:45:12.280
Maybe it wasn't, but
it was in your pail.

838
00:45:15.393 --> 00:45:17.224
I'm leaving, sister.

839
00:45:20.565 --> 00:45:21.964
Miss Bragg.

840
00:45:22.033 --> 00:45:23.432
May I have a word with you,
Professor Potts?


841
00:45:23.501 --> 00:45:24.900
That music, is it coming from next door?

842
00:45:24.969 --> 00:45:27.403
From this door, and that's what
I want to talk to you about.


843
00:45:27.472 --> 00:45:29.099
Either she goes or I go.

844
00:45:29.173 --> 00:45:32.370
- You're speaking of Miss O'Shea?
- I am, Professor Potts.


845
00:45:32.443 --> 00:45:36.743
That is the kind of woman
that makes whole civilizations topple.


846
00:45:36.814 --> 00:45:40.944
It's always been my pride to scrupulously,
untiringly, efficiently...


847
00:45:41.019 --> 00:45:43.385
Now, now, Miss Bragg,
you've split that infinitive three times.


848
00:45:43.454 --> 00:45:45.752
I repeat, either she goes or I go.

849
00:45:45.823 --> 00:45:48.656
I don't like ultimata, Miss Bragg,
but I shall look into the matter.


850
00:45:48.726 --> 00:45:51.923
Don't look into the matter,
look into the library.


851
00:46:08.212 --> 00:46:10.544
Hiya, Pottsy, come on, hook on!

852
00:46:10.615 --> 00:46:12.242
I feel so abandoned.

853
00:46:21.526 --> 00:46:23.187
Hey, what's the big idea?

854
00:46:23.261 --> 00:46:26.628
As soon as you gentlemen get your breath,
we had better have a conference.


855
00:46:26.697 --> 00:46:28.187
Will you please leave the room,
Miss O'Shea?


856
00:46:28.266 --> 00:46:32.225
- But we've only just started.
- lf you please, Miss O'Shea.


857
00:46:32.303 --> 00:46:34.237
Loose-tooth again.

858
00:46:34.305 --> 00:46:36.170
Now, if you gentlemen will be kind enough

859
00:46:37.842 --> 00:46:39.707
to get together all that you've written
in the last three days...


860
00:46:47.919 --> 00:46:49.045
Well, it's about time.

861
00:46:49.120 --> 00:46:51.020
I thought you two had amnesia
and forgot where you parked me.


862
00:46:51.089 --> 00:46:52.113
Hold the phone, Sugie.

863
00:46:52.190 --> 00:46:54.488
Dropping me on the doorstep
like a throwaway for a credit dentist.


864
00:46:54.559 --> 00:46:56.584
- You said it was for one night.
- Sugie, for snap's sake.


865
00:46:56.661 --> 00:46:58.891
You're as hot as a pistol.
The DA's got 100 men on the job.


866
00:46:58.963 --> 00:47:01.591
Why, they're squeezing this town
through a sieve, borough by borough.


867
00:47:01.666 --> 00:47:02.894
You tell her, Pastrami.

868
00:47:02.967 --> 00:47:05.629
They're tailing us, Sugie. Took us
three hours to get here from 48th Street.


869
00:47:05.703 --> 00:47:07.500
Detoured through Jamaica, Long Island
to shake them off.


870
00:47:07.572 --> 00:47:08.630
Okay, you wait here.

871
00:47:08.706 --> 00:47:10.105
I'll get my things together
in two seconds flat.


872
00:47:10.174 --> 00:47:11.573
Hey, wait a minute, Sugie.

873
00:47:11.642 --> 00:47:15.305
- We got a surprise for you.
- You ain't leaving, not right yet.


874
00:47:15.379 --> 00:47:16.641
I'm not? Joe's out, isn't he?

875
00:47:16.714 --> 00:47:19.683
Yeah, but for how long? They're laying
for you so they can get him back.


876
00:47:19.750 --> 00:47:20.774
That's the surprise.

877
00:47:20.852 --> 00:47:23.582
I'm supposed to stay in this old mans'
home till the moths eat holes in me?


878
00:47:23.654 --> 00:47:26.145
Say, when I say a surprise,
I mean a surprise.


879
00:47:26.224 --> 00:47:27.919
Go on, flash it to her.

880
00:47:27.992 --> 00:47:30.358
Put on your sunglasses, Sugie.

881
00:47:30.995 --> 00:47:33.862
- Oh, boy.
- Seven grand boiled into that one, Sugie.


882
00:47:34.665 --> 00:47:37.031
Joe doesn't have to bribe me
just because I do him a little favor.


883
00:47:37.101 --> 00:47:38.659
It's not a bribe,
don't take it like that.

884
00:47:38.736 --> 00:47:39.896
Let him try and get it back though.

885
00:47:39.971 --> 00:47:41.131
Say, it's not your size, is it?

886
00:47:41.205 --> 00:47:43.070
lt'll do, if I have
to whittle down my finger.

887
00:47:43.141 --> 00:47:45.371
Third finger, left hand, Sugie.

888
00:47:45.443 --> 00:47:47.536
- Who do you think you're kidding?
- The future Mrs. Joe Lilac.


889
00:47:47.612 --> 00:47:49.409
- Come again?
- Wedding bells, sweetheart.


890
00:47:49.480 --> 00:47:51.072
Joe and the lawyer have got it
all figured out.


891
00:47:51.149 --> 00:47:52.946
Yeah, a wife can't testify
against husband, see.


892
00:47:53.017 --> 00:47:54.348
Don't put it like that, you dope.

893
00:47:54.418 --> 00:47:58.616
Say, he's been thataway about you
ever since he first picked you out.


894
00:47:58.689 --> 00:48:01.123
Yeah, but it took the DA
to make him pop the question.


895
00:48:01.192 --> 00:48:02.318
He sent you a love message.

896
00:48:02.393 --> 00:48:05.419
He says to tell you he gets more bang
out of you than any dame he ever knew.


897
00:48:05.496 --> 00:48:08.693
And he's the top, Sugie,
do you realize that? He's the top.


898
00:48:08.799 --> 00:48:10.266
Mrs. Joe Lilac.

899
00:48:10.334 --> 00:48:12.996
Third Avenue girl
in the major league at last.


900
00:48:13.070 --> 00:48:15.368
Wait till they find out,
those other dolls in the show.


901
00:48:15.439 --> 00:48:17.532
Watch me break their crockery with this.

902
00:48:17.608 --> 00:48:19.200
Here, here,
the wedding's got to be a fast one, though.


903
00:48:19.277 --> 00:48:20.539
Over in New Jersey someplace.

904
00:48:20.611 --> 00:48:23.045
Now, this is the application for the license,
and you sign right here.


905
00:48:23.114 --> 00:48:24.775
- Will I? You got a pen?
- Yeah.


906
00:48:24.849 --> 00:48:27.079
- Unscrew it for Mrs. Lilac.
- Right here, right here.


907
00:48:27.151 --> 00:48:28.243
You know, I can't make up my mind.

908
00:48:28.319 --> 00:48:32.653
Will I continue my night club career
or bust in on the Helen Hayes racket?


909
00:48:32.723 --> 00:48:34.486
Say, this ought to be signed
before a notary public.


910
00:48:34.559 --> 00:48:37.255
I'm a notary public,
permission expires 1943.


911
00:48:37.328 --> 00:48:39.057
Were those pajamas a good investment.

912
00:48:39.130 --> 00:48:41.155
You'll get the final dope
by tomorrow morning.


913
00:48:41.232 --> 00:48:42.324
Joe will phone around 10:00.

914
00:48:42.400 --> 00:48:44.834
Now, meantime lie low
and stick close to the Ameche.


915
00:48:44.902 --> 00:48:47.200
- Okay, the what?
- The telephone.


916
00:48:51.676 --> 00:48:54.509
- Miss Sugarpuss.
- You'd better duck.


917
00:48:54.579 --> 00:48:56.672
- Okay, 10:00, I'll be waiting.
- Okay, okay.


918
00:48:56.747 --> 00:48:58.715
- Miss Sugarpuss.
- Here I am.


919
00:48:58.783 --> 00:49:00.683
Just getting a little air.

920
00:49:00.751 --> 00:49:03.311
- Miss O'Shea.
- What's buzzing, cousin?


921
00:49:03.387 --> 00:49:05.787
Professor Potts would...

922
00:49:05.856 --> 00:49:08.723
He wishes to speak to you.

923
00:49:09.093 --> 00:49:10.355
- Yes.
- Yes.


924
00:49:10.428 --> 00:49:12.658
Don't worry, kids, cheer up.

925
00:49:14.198 --> 00:49:16.428
- Shut the door, please.
- Sure.


926
00:49:20.504 --> 00:49:23.962
- Take this chair, please, Miss O'Shea.
- This particular one?


927
00:49:24.041 --> 00:49:25.167
Okay.

928
00:49:28.312 --> 00:49:30.280
- Open your mouth, please.
- Hmm?


929
00:49:30.348 --> 00:49:32.816
Open your mouth. Wider.

930
00:49:33.951 --> 00:49:34.975
Thank you.

931
00:49:35.052 --> 00:49:36.610
- Can I close it now?
- Please do.


932
00:49:36.687 --> 00:49:37.984
- Okay.
- Miss O'Shea.


933
00:49:38.055 --> 00:49:39.079
Yeah?

934
00:49:39.156 --> 00:49:42.523
Circumstances, under, over which
neither of us has the least control,


935
00:49:42.593 --> 00:49:45.653
force me to a step
I am most reluctant to take.


936
00:49:46.964 --> 00:49:49.956
The sky is perfectly clear.
The thermometer stands at 76.


937
00:49:50.034 --> 00:49:53.128
Your throat seems quite normal.
I must ask you to leave.


938
00:49:53.204 --> 00:49:55.263
Leave here? Why?

939
00:49:55.339 --> 00:49:58.172
Miss O'Shea,
I want you to look at our project,


940
00:49:58.242 --> 00:50:01.405
I mean the encyclopedia, as a voyage,

941
00:50:01.479 --> 00:50:03.947
a long, hard, tedious one.

942
00:50:04.015 --> 00:50:06.074
A voyage from "A" to "Z."

943
00:50:06.150 --> 00:50:08.015
Now, when the Foundation
launched our vessel,


944
00:50:08.085 --> 00:50:12.545
it very wisely followed an old rule
of the sea, no women aboard.


945
00:50:12.623 --> 00:50:15.490
It chose a crew of single men
with nothing to distract them


946
00:50:15.559 --> 00:50:17.151
from the course they were to sail.

947
00:50:17.228 --> 00:50:20.425
Say, junior, couldn't stop
walking around a little, could you?


948
00:50:20.498 --> 00:50:23.626
For four days, we have been drifting,
Miss O'Shea.


949
00:50:23.701 --> 00:50:26.033
The needle of the compass
no longer points to the magnetic pole.


950
00:50:26.103 --> 00:50:28.731
It points, if I may
say so, to your ankles.

951
00:50:28.806 --> 00:50:31.104
Come now, Admiral,
a bunch of grown men,


952
00:50:31.175 --> 00:50:33.166
they've seen a pair of ankles before.

953
00:50:33.244 --> 00:50:34.734
Not for nine years.

954
00:50:34.812 --> 00:50:38.805
Except for the singularly uninspiring
underpinnings of Miss Bragg.


955
00:50:38.883 --> 00:50:40.282
Now, my colleagues...

956
00:50:40.351 --> 00:50:42.581
If you think I'm bothering them,
I'll sit on my legs.


957
00:50:42.653 --> 00:50:45.053
- And I'll do it in my room or in the kitchen.
- Too late.


958
00:50:45.122 --> 00:50:48.353
- You must leave, Miss O'Shea.
- Well, I can't leave now.


959
00:50:48.426 --> 00:50:50.917
How about that slang?
It's not finished yet.


960
00:50:50.995 --> 00:50:52.895
There's a lot of words
we haven't caught up with.


961
00:50:52.963 --> 00:50:55.796
For instance, do you know what this
means, "I'll get you on the Ameche"?


962
00:50:55.866 --> 00:50:57.094
- No.
- Of course, you don't.


963
00:50:57.168 --> 00:50:58.533
An Ameche is the telephone.

964
00:50:58.602 --> 00:51:00.433
- On account of he invented it.
- Oh, no, he didn't.


965
00:51:00.504 --> 00:51:05.134
- You know, in the movies.
- I see what you mean. Very interesting.


966
00:51:05.276 --> 00:51:08.939
Make no mistake, I shall regret
the absence of your keen mind.


967
00:51:09.013 --> 00:51:13.074
Unfortunately, it is inseparable
from an extremely disturbing body.


968
00:51:14.452 --> 00:51:16.750
All right. I'll go, only don't shove.

969
00:51:16.821 --> 00:51:19.517
- I'll leave sometime tomorrow.
- Not tomorrow. Right away.


970
00:51:19.590 --> 00:51:21.717
- But I tell you I've got a...
- I insist, Miss O'Shea.


971
00:51:21.792 --> 00:51:23.225
Oh, Crabapple Annie.

972
00:51:23.294 --> 00:51:24.955
- Listen, Pottsy...
- Crabapple Annie?


973
00:51:25.029 --> 00:51:27.190
Why, that implies
that I'm puritanical and narrow-minded.


974
00:51:27.264 --> 00:51:28.288
Yeah.

975
00:51:28.366 --> 00:51:31.062
I am a perfectly normal man
with perfectly normal instincts.


976
00:51:31.135 --> 00:51:33.603
- But an awful high boiling point.
- Not even that.


977
00:51:33.671 --> 00:51:36.469
I, too, have been acutely aware
of your presence.


978
00:51:36.540 --> 00:51:38.337
- You have?
- Twice, to be exact.


979
00:51:38.409 --> 00:51:39.740
Once when you leaned over my shoulder

980
00:51:39.810 --> 00:51:41.744
to correct my spelling of
the word "boogie-woogie,"


981
00:51:41.812 --> 00:51:43.541
I could feel your breath on my ear.

982
00:51:43.614 --> 00:51:46.048
And yesterday afternoon when you
happened to stand against the window


983
00:51:46.117 --> 00:51:48.415
with the sunlight in your hair.

984
00:51:50.154 --> 00:51:53.317
- What'd you do about it?
- I left the room,


985
00:51:53.391 --> 00:51:54.983
dipped my handkerchief in cold water

986
00:51:55.059 --> 00:51:56.959
and applied it to the back of
my neck right there,


987
00:51:57.027 --> 00:52:00.087
- where the nerve center is.
- That's cute.


988
00:52:00.164 --> 00:52:03.224
You see, that's the basic difference
between me and the other professors.


989
00:52:03.300 --> 00:52:06.030
We are all beguiled,
but I am relatively young.


990
00:52:06.103 --> 00:52:07.400
I can suppress temptation.

991
00:52:07.471 --> 00:52:11.032
I generate enough energy
to take precautionary measures.


992
00:52:12.243 --> 00:52:15.701
A little sun on my hair
and you had to water your neck.


993
00:52:17.782 --> 00:52:20.216
Perhaps I shouldn't have mentioned it,
Miss O'Shea,


994
00:52:20.284 --> 00:52:22.149
but I'm merely trying
to point out the fact

995
00:52:22.219 --> 00:52:25.052
that the success of our enterprise
is at stake.


996
00:52:25.122 --> 00:52:27.181
I want you to...

997
00:52:31.028 --> 00:52:32.552
Cooperate.

998
00:52:32.630 --> 00:52:34.393
I want you to leave.

999
00:52:35.499 --> 00:52:37.296
All right, I'll go.

1000
00:52:38.202 --> 00:52:41.433
But if I'm going to go anyway,
I guess I might as well spill it.


1001
00:52:41.505 --> 00:52:43.769
Spill it? Spill what?

1002
00:52:43.841 --> 00:52:45.604
Why do you suppose
I came here in the first place?


1003
00:52:45.676 --> 00:52:46.734
To help with the research.

1004
00:52:46.811 --> 00:52:48.802
- I did not. I came on account of you.
- Me?


1005
00:52:48.879 --> 00:52:50.813
And not on account of
you needed some slang.


1006
00:52:50.881 --> 00:52:52.576
On account of
because I wanted to see you again.


1007
00:52:52.650 --> 00:52:55.244
Miss O'Shea, the construction
"on account of because"


1008
00:52:55.319 --> 00:52:57.014
outrages every grammatical law.

1009
00:52:57.087 --> 00:52:59.885
So what? I came on account of
because I couldn't stop thinking about you


1010
00:52:59.957 --> 00:53:01.720
after you left my dressing room.

1011
00:53:01.792 --> 00:53:06.354
On account of because I thought
you were big and cute and pretty.


1012
00:53:06.430 --> 00:53:07.761
- Pretty?
- Yeah, I mean you.


1013
00:53:07.832 --> 00:53:11.199
Maybe I'm just crazy, but to me,
you're a regular yum-yum type.


1014
00:53:11.268 --> 00:53:13.259
- Yum-yum?
- Yeah, don't you know what that means?


1015
00:53:13.337 --> 00:53:14.395
No, we never got to that.

1016
00:53:14.472 --> 00:53:16.167
Well, we've got to it now,
and I'm glad it's out.


1017
00:53:16.240 --> 00:53:17.969
I don't give a whoop
whether the others went for me.


1018
00:53:18.042 --> 00:53:19.907
You're the one I'm wacky about,
just plain wacky.


1019
00:53:19.977 --> 00:53:21.740
- Can you understand that?
- Please, Miss O'Shea.


1020
00:53:21.812 --> 00:53:23.973
Oh, please, nothing.
Maybe you can generate or whatever it is


1021
00:53:24.048 --> 00:53:26.312
for all that suppress business, but...

1022
00:53:26.383 --> 00:53:28.681
I can't. No, you're too tall.

1023
00:53:31.422 --> 00:53:32.684
- What are you doing?
- You'll find out.


1024
00:53:32.756 --> 00:53:34.348
Those are Professor Gurkakoff's
reference books.


1025
00:53:34.425 --> 00:53:36.484
- Now, isn't that just too bad!
- And they're very...


1026
00:53:36.560 --> 00:53:38.152
- That's perfect.
- What are you going to do?


1027
00:53:38.229 --> 00:53:40.993
Come here,
I'm going to show you what yum-yum is.


1028
00:53:41.065 --> 00:53:42.430
Here's yum.

1029
00:53:43.968 --> 00:53:45.799
Here's the other yum.

1030
00:53:47.805 --> 00:53:49.568
And here's yum-yum.

1031
00:53:53.444 --> 00:53:54.775
Excuse me.

1032
00:53:55.513 --> 00:53:56.537
Hey, where are you going?

1033
00:54:08.025 --> 00:54:11.085
Did you see?
He practically stepped on my hand.


1034
00:54:11.161 --> 00:54:12.992
- Three steps at a time.
- Shot out of a gun.


1035
00:54:13.063 --> 00:54:14.724
- But where is he going?
- Why?


1036
00:54:14.798 --> 00:54:18.495
To get a razor strop, I hope,
and I hope he knows where to apply it.


1037
00:54:23.440 --> 00:54:27.342
- Well, Professor Potts?
- Yes, Miss Bragg.


1038
00:54:27.411 --> 00:54:30.710
Will one of you call a taxi
from the corner for Miss O'Shea?


1039
00:54:31.382 --> 00:54:33.373
- Right away.
- Thank you.


1040
00:54:39.290 --> 00:54:41.656
- Fine business.
- I beg your pardon?


1041
00:54:41.725 --> 00:54:43.352
What's the idea of
running out on me like that?


1042
00:54:43.427 --> 00:54:45.520
Nothing, nothing.

1043
00:54:46.096 --> 00:54:49.156
The last few minutes
only confirmed my former decision.


1044
00:54:49.233 --> 00:54:51.224
Your further presence here would be fatal.

1045
00:54:51.302 --> 00:54:54.863
You must get me out of your mind
just as I must get you out of this house.


1046
00:54:54.939 --> 00:54:58.306
- Your hair's wet.
- Well, never mind, please.


1047
00:54:58.375 --> 00:55:00.866
- Well, it is wet.
- Well, what of it?


1048
00:55:00.945 --> 00:55:02.173
Nothing, I just happened to mention it.

1049
00:55:02.246 --> 00:55:04.840
- Well, forget it, please.
- Okay, okay.


1050
00:55:05.549 --> 00:55:08.575
Now to get back to the subject
under discussion.


1051
00:55:08.652 --> 00:55:12.019
It would be idle of me to deny that I, too,
feel the affinity


1052
00:55:12.089 --> 00:55:15.456
that you mentioned a few minutes ago,
very strongly.


1053
00:55:15.526 --> 00:55:17.391
After three years,
when my work is finished,


1054
00:55:17.461 --> 00:55:20.259
perhaps we can take
up where we left off.

1055
00:55:20.331 --> 00:55:25.268
In the meantime, I hope we can keep up
some sort of correspondence.


1056
00:55:26.503 --> 00:55:30.599
- Would you, Miss Sugarpuss?
- Oh, Pottsy.


1057
00:55:31.909 --> 00:55:35.174
I know that's the way I feel, too,
but it has to be.


1058
00:55:36.714 --> 00:55:41.048
Sugarpuss, before you go, would you...

1059
00:55:47.791 --> 00:55:49.258
Would you

1060
00:55:50.794 --> 00:55:52.694
yum me just once more?

1061
00:56:00.070 --> 00:56:02.766
- It seems so unnecessary.
- Yes.


1062
00:56:02.840 --> 00:56:04.467
- Yes.
- The taxi's here.


1063
00:56:04.575 --> 00:56:06.065
I'll tell him.

1064
00:56:11.448 --> 00:56:14.940
Professor Potts,
the taxi for that young woman is here.


1065
00:56:17.054 --> 00:56:18.351
The taxi.